"# Appendix C — Resolution

Where the entire proof-search machinery of first-order logic collapses
to one rule and one algorithm.

*Resolution* is a proof rule invented by Robinson in 1965. It works on
formulas in *conjunctive normal form* (chapter 1) — a big AND of
*clauses*, each clause a big OR of *literals*. A literal is either an
atomic formula or its negation.

The rule: from two clauses
- `C₁ = L ∨ D₁` (contains literal L)
- `C₂ = ¬L ∨ D₂` (contains its negation)

derive the *resolvent*
- `D₁ ∨ D₂`

The complementary literals cancel; the remaining disjunctions merge.

That is the whole rule. Every provable first-order sentence can be
proved by repeated application of this rule (with unification, for
predicate-logic cases). And there is a nearly-mechanical algorithm for
applying it — resolution has been the workhorse of automated theorem
proving for sixty years.

## Propositional resolution

Start with the propositional version. We work with clauses represented
as sets of literals.

```scheme
;; A literal is either a symbol or (list 'not symbol).
;; A clause is a list of literals.
;; A CNF formula is a list of clauses.

(define (literal-negate lit)
  (cond
    ((symbol? lit) (list 'not lit))
    ((and (pair? lit) (eq? (car lit) 'not)) (cadr lit))))

(define (literals-complementary? l1 l2)
  (equal? l1 (literal-negate l2)))

(define (resolve clause1 clause2)
  ;; Return list of resolvents (usually one, sometimes more).
  (apply append
    (map (lambda (l1)
           (apply append
             (map (lambda (l2)
                    (if (literals-complementary? l1 l2)
                        (list (dedupe
                                (append (remove-once l1 clause1)
                                        (remove-once l2 clause2))))
                        '()))
                  clause2)))
         clause1)))

(define (remove-once x xs)
  (cond ((null? xs) '())
        ((equal? (car xs) x) (cdr xs))
        (else (cons (car xs) (remove-once x (cdr xs))))))
```

Try it.

```scheme
(resolve '(P Q) '((not P) R))
;; => ((Q R))    ; resolvent: Q ∨ R

(resolve '(P) '((not P)))
;; => (())       ; the empty clause: contradiction!
```

The *empty clause* — the disjunction of zero literals — is *false*.
Deriving the empty clause means the input set of clauses is
unsatisfiable, which means the negation of what we were trying to
prove is unsatisfiable, which means what we were trying to prove is
valid.

## The resolution algorithm

To prove that a formula φ is a theorem:

1. Negate: ¬φ.
2. Convert ¬φ to CNF.
3. Repeatedly resolve pairs of clauses; add the resolvents to the
   set.
4. If we derive the empty clause, φ is a theorem.
5. If no new resolvents can be produced and the empty clause has not
   appeared, φ is not a theorem.

```scheme
(define (prove-by-resolution formula)
  ;; Try to prove formula by refuting its negation.
  (let ((clauses (cnf-of (list 'not formula))))
    (let loop ((c clauses))
      (cond
        ((member '() c) 'proved)      ; empty clause derived
        (else
         (let ((new-resolvents (all-new-resolvents c)))
           (cond
             ((null? new-resolvents) 'not-proved)
             (else (loop (append new-resolvents c))))))))))

(define (all-new-resolvents clauses)
  ;; Every pair of clauses; collect their resolvents; drop those
  ;; already in `clauses`.
  (apply append
    (map (lambda (c1)
           (apply append
             (map (lambda (c2)
                    (filter (lambda (r) (not (member r clauses)))
                            (resolve c1 c2)))
                  clauses)))
         clauses)))
```

This is the *saturation* strategy: keep resolving until either the
empty clause appears or no new resolvents can be produced. For
propositional logic this always terminates because there are only
finitely many possible clauses.

## Predicate-logic resolution: adding unification

For first-order logic we need one more piece: *unification* (Appendix
B). When we resolve two clauses containing predicate applications with
variables, we may need to unify the literals to make them
complementary.

    C₁ = (P X) ∨ Q
    C₂ = (not (P a)) ∨ R

The literals `(P X)` and `(not (P a))` are not directly complementary,
but they can be made complementary by unifying `X` with `a`. After
unification, the resolvent is `σ(Q ∨ R)` where σ = {X → a}.

```scheme
(define (resolve-first-order clause1 clause2)
  ;; Try to resolve using unification of literals.
  (apply append
    (map (lambda (l1)
           (apply append
             (map (lambda (l2)
                    (let ((unifier (try-complementary-unification l1 l2)))
                      (if (eq? unifier 'fail)
                          '()
                          (list (apply-subst-to-clause
                                 unifier
                                 (dedupe
                                  (append (remove-once l1 clause1)
                                          (remove-once l2 clause2))))))))
                  clause2)))
         clause1)))

(define (try-complementary-unification l1 l2)
  ;; If l1 is (P ...) and l2 is (not (P ...)), unify the atomic parts.
  (cond
    ((and (pair? l2) (eq? (car l2) 'not))
     (unify l1 (cadr l2) '()))
    ((and (pair? l1) (eq? (car l1) 'not))
     (unify (cadr l1) l2 '()))
    (else 'fail)))
```

With unification, resolution becomes complete for first-order logic —
that is, if a first-order sentence is valid, resolution will find a
refutation of its negation (given enough time). This is a corollary of
Godel's completeness theorem plus Robinson's completeness proof for
resolution.

## Refinements

Naive resolution is complete but *inefficient*. The set of possible
resolvents grows explosively. Real theorem provers use *refinements*
that restrict which resolutions are allowed:

- **Set-of-support.** Only resolve pairs at least one of which comes
  from the negation of the goal. Focuses search on the goal.
- **Unit resolution.** Only resolve when one clause is a single
  literal (a *unit* clause). Fast; incomplete.
- **Linear resolution.** Each resolution step uses the most recent
  resolvent. Structures the search as a linear chain.
- **Ordered resolution.** Impose an ordering on literals; only resolve
  on maximal literals. Restricts search dramatically.
- **Semantic resolution.** Use a specific model to guide which
  resolvents are useful.

Combinations of these refinements are what powers modern first-order
provers like Vampire, E, and SPASS. They can solve problems with tens
of thousands of clauses in seconds.

## The connection to logic programming

*Horn clauses* are clauses with at most one positive literal:

    ¬A ∨ ¬B ∨ ¬C ∨ D             (the rule: D if A and B and C)
    D                              (the fact: D holds)
    ¬A ∨ ¬B ∨ ¬C                  (the goal: prove A and B and C — false statement)

Prolog is essentially *SLD-resolution* — a specific refinement of
resolution for Horn clauses. Every Prolog derivation is a resolution
proof; every unification is the Appendix B algorithm. Prolog was born
directly from Robinson's resolution principle, plus the observation
that Horn clauses give a decidable resolution strategy.

## What resolution cannot do

Resolution is complete for *first-order* logic. It is not complete for:

- Second-order logic (no algorithm is complete for full second-order).
- Modal logic (needs special calculi).
- Non-monotonic reasoning (fundamentally different structure).

For these, other calculi apply: tableaux, sequent calculi, model
elimination, satisfiability modulo theories (SMT).

Resolution is also *semi-decidable*: if a formula is provable,
resolution finds a proof; if not provable, resolution may run forever.
This is a corollary of the undecidability of first-order validity
(Church 1936).

## What to try

Implement propositional resolution end-to-end: parse a propositional
formula, convert to CNF (using the pipeline sketched in chapter 1),
call the resolution loop, report the result.

Extend to first-order resolution with unification. Try the classic
example: from *all men are mortal* and *Socrates is a man*, derive
*Socrates is mortal* by resolution.

Add the *set-of-support* refinement. Compare the number of resolvents
generated with and without it on a small example.

## Closing

Resolution collapses first-order proof into one rule plus unification.
It is complete, semi-decidable, and remarkably efficient with the
right refinements. Every modern first-order theorem prover descends
from Robinson's 1965 formulation.

This appendix's implementations are the seed. Adding refinements,
efficient indexing, and clause management scales the machinery to
industrially useful sizes.
"
